# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1877-louisville-grays-scandal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The Knopf publishing house is associated with the borzoi logo in its colophon, which was designed by co-founder Blanche Knopf in 1925.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf Sr. along with Blanche Knopf, on a $5,000 advance from his father, Samuel Knopf.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The first office was located in New York's Candler Building.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The publishing house was officially incorporated in 1918, with Alfred Knopf as president, Blanche Knopf as vice president, and Samuel Knopf as treasurer.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] From the start, Knopf focused on European translations and high-brow works of literature.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Among their initial publications were French author Émile Augier's *Four Plays*, Russian writer Nikolai Gogol's *Taras Bulba*, Polish novelist Stanisław Przybyszewski's novel *Homo Sapiens*, and French writer Guy de Maupassant's *Yvette, a Novelette, and Ten Other Stories*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] During World War I these books were cheap to obtain and helped establish Knopf as an American firm publishing European works.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Their first bestseller was a new edition of *Green Mansions*, a novel by W.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Hudson which went through nine printings by 1919 and sold over 20,000 copies.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Their first original American novel, *The Three Black Pennys* by Joseph Hergesheimer, was published in 1917.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] With the start of the 1920s Knopf began using innovative advertising techniques to draw attention to their books and authors.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Beginning in 1920, Knopf produced a chapbook for the purpose of promoting new books.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] *The Borzoi* was published periodically over the years, the first being a hardback called *The Borzoi* and sometimes quarterly as *The Borzoi Quarterly*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] For Floyd Dell's coming-of-age novel, *Moon-Calf*, they paid men to walk the streets of the financial and theatre districts dressed in artist costumes with sandwich boards.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The placards had a copy of the book for browsing and directed interested buyers to local book shops.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The unique look of their books along with their expertise in advertising their authors drew Willa Cather to leave her previous publisher Houghton Mifflin to join Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] As she was still under contract for her novels, the Knopfs suggested publishing a collection of her short stories, *Youth and the Bright Medusa*, in 1920.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Cather was pleased with the results and the advertisement of the book in *The New Republic* and would go on to publish sixteen books with Knopf, including their first Pulitzer Prize winner, *One of Ours*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Before they had married, Alfred had promised Blanche that they would be equal partners in the publishing company, but it was clear by the company's fifth anniversary that this was not to be the case.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf published a celebratory fifth-anniversary book in which Alfred was the focus of anecdotes by authors and Blanche's name was only mentioned once to note that "Mrs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] This despite ample evidence from authors and others that Blanche was in fact the soul of the company.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] This was covered extensively in *The Lady with the Borzoi* by Laura Claridge.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In 1923, Knopf also started publishing periodicals, beginning with *The American Mercury*, founded by H.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Mencken and George Jean Nathan, which it published through 1934.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Also in 1923, Knopf published Kahlil Gibran's *The Prophet*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf had published Gibran's earlier works which had disappointing sales.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In its first year, *The Prophet* only sold 1,159 copies.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] It would double sales the next year and keep doubling becoming one of the firm's most successful books.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Approaching its 100 year anniversary in 2023, *The Prophet* has been translated into over 100 languages and has never gone out of print for Knopf.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In the 1920s, Knopf sometimes withdrew or censored their books when threatened by John Sumner, such as Floyd Dell's *Janet March* or George Egerton's 1899 translation of *Hunger*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Koshland joined the company in 1934, and worked with the firm for more than fifty years, rising to take the positions of president and chairman of the board.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Blanche became president in 1957 when Alfred became chairman of the board, and worked steadily for the firm until her death in 1966.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf retired in 1972, becoming chairman emeritus of the firm until his death in 1984.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf also had a summer home in Purchase, New York.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Following the Good Neighbor policy, Blanche Knopf visited South America in 1942, so the firm could start producing texts from there.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] She was one of the first publishers to visit Europe after World War II.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Her trips, and those of other editors, brought in new writers from Europe, South America, and Asia.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Alfred traveled to Brazil in 1961, which spurred a corresponding interest on his part in South America.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Penn Publishing Company was acquired in 1943.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The Knopfs' son, Alfred "Pat" Jr., was hired on as secretary and trade books manager after the war.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In 1957, editor Judith Jones joined Knopf.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Jones, who had discovered *Anne Frank: Diary of a Young Girl* while working at Doubleday, acquired Simone Beck, Louisette Bertholle and Julia Child's *Mastering the Art of French Cooking* for Knopf.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Jones would remain with Knopf, retiring in 2011 as a senior editor and vice-president after a career that included working with John Updike and Anne Tyler.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Pat Knopf left his parents' publishing company in 1959 to launch his own, Atheneum Publishers, with two other partners.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The story made the front page of *The New York Times*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In a 1957 advertisement in *The Atlantic Monthly*, Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The credo includes a list of what Knopf's beliefs for publishing including the statement that he never published an unworthy book.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In 1960, Random House acquired Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] It is believed that the decision to sell was prompted by Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf Jr., leaving Knopf to found his own book company, Atheneum Books, in 1959.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Since its founding, Knopf has paid close attention to design and typography, employing notable designers and typographers including William Addison Dwiggins, Harry Ford, Steven Heller, Chip Kidd, Lorraine Louie, Peter Mendelsund, Bruce Rogers, Rudolf Ruzicka, and Beatrice Warde.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf books conclude with an unnumbered page titled "A Note on the Type", which describes the history of the typeface used for the book.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In addition, Knopf books date the year of the book's current printing on the title page.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf published textbooks until 1988, when Random House's schools and colleges division was sold to McGraw Hill.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In 1991, Knopf revived the "Everyman's Library" series, originally published in England in the early 20th century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] This series consists of classics of world literature in affordable hardcover editions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The series has grown over the years to include lines of *Children's Classics* and *Pocket Poets*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Random House was acquired by Bertelsmann AG in 1998.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In late 2008 and early 2009, the Knopf Publishing Group merged with Doubleday to form the Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Random House has been owned since its 2013 merger of Penguin Group by Penguin Random House, a joint venture between Bertelsmann (53%) and Pearson PLC (47%).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Many of Knopf's hardcover books are published later as Vintage paperbacks.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Vintage Books is a sister imprint of Random House.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In October 2012, Bertelsmann entered into talks with rival conglomerate Pearson plc, over the possibility of combining their respective publishing companies, Random House and Penguin Group.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The merger was completed on 1 July 2013 and the new company is Penguin Random House.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Bertelsmann owned 53% of the joint venture while Pearson owned 47%.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] At the time of the acquisition the combined companies controlled 25% of the book business, with more than 10,000 employees and 250 independent publishing imprints and with about $3.9 billion in annual revenues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The move to consolidate was to provide leverage against Amazon.com and battle the shrinking state of bookstores.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] In 2015, Knopf celebrated its 100th anniversary by publishing a commemorative book, *Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] While there have been many notable editors at Knopf there have only been four editors-in-chief: Alfred A.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf, Sr., Robert Gottlieb, Sonny Mehta (who died in 2019) and Jordan Pavlin.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Knopf also employed literary scouts to good advantage.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Hamilton, Kazuo Ishiguro, John Keegan, Nella Larsen, John le Carré, Jack London, Gabriel García Márquez, Cormac McCarthy, Toni Morrison, Alice Munro, Haruki Murakami, Cynthia Ozick, Christopher Paolini, Edgar Allan Poe, Ezra Pound, Anne Rice, Dorothy Richardson, Stephen M.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Silverman, Oswald Spengler, Susan Swan, Donna Tartt, Barbara W.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Tuchman, Anne Tyler, John Updike, Andrew Vachss, James D.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] The logo for Knopf is a Russian wolfhound or Borzoi.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/a-a-knopf] Blanche Knopf suggested the Borzoi for the logo to imply motion and the logo was used on both the spine and the title page of their books.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] Nichols got his start at third base for the 1875 Brooklyn Atlantics of the National Association.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] He batted only .153 in 32 games played that season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] The following year, after the collapse of the Association, he played for the New York Mutuals of the new National League and didn't fare much better, hitting .179 in 57 games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] It was for the Louisville Grays in 1877 that he would gain infamy.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] It was determined that he was involved in throwing games for money along with teammates George Hall, Jim Devlin, and Bill Craver.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] As a personal friend of Hall, he was brought in to play third base at Hall's insistence to replace Bill Hauge when he had to take time off due to injury.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] At this point, Louisville was in first place, but soon after Nichols' arrival, the team began to lose games at an alarming rate.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] Chase started to become suspicious when Nichols was still playing even though he continued to make key errors when Hauge was well enough to return to his starting position.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] His suspicion was confirmed when he received a couple telegrams instructing him to watch his players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] Chase confronted the players, and Hall and Devlin confessed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] The matter was referred to National League president William Hulbert, and Nichols was formally banned from Major League Baseball on December 4, 1877.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] Nichols came to the United States from England in 1861.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] After his banishment from baseball, he spent most of his life in the Brooklyn, New York area, got married and raised a family.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] He worked at various jobs, including as a shipping clerk and inspector, and was very remorseful about his role in the scandal, making many unsuccessful attempts to earn reinstatement.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] He died in Richmond Hill, New York, at the age of 84.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/al-nichols] He was cremated and interred at Green-Wood Cemetery in Brooklyn.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Before his baseball career, Craver had served in the military during the Civil War with the 13th Heavy Artillery Regiment out of New York.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He enlisted on January 21, 1864, as a Private in Company K, and mustered out on June 28 in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] When the war, and his military career were over, he began his organized baseball career as a catcher in 1866 with the Union Baseball Club of Rensselaer County, which became the Unions of Lansingburgh.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The Unions gained the nickname of Haymakers in August of that year after a visit to the Capitoline Grounds and the Elysian Fields.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Later, in 1870, while playing for a Chicago team, he was accused of breaking his contract with the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] In 1871, Craver joined the Troy Haymakers, who entered the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the league's first season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He played second base, and after just four games, he replaced Lip Pike as manager.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He played well, batting .322, but the team finished in seventh place.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] For the next two seasons, he joined the Baltimore Canaries, the first of which he was player-manager.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He was replaced at manager later in the year by Everett Mills, but stayed with the team through the 1873 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Playing for the Philadelphia White Stockings in 1874, he led the league in games played, and as a second baseman, he led the league in putouts and errors.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Craver had his best offensive season that year, batting .343 and leading the league in stolen bases.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] In 1875, he moved over the Philadelphia Centennials.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He played in just 13 games for them when, together with George Bechtel, he was traded to the Philadelphia Athletics to replace injured players Dave Eggler and Wes Fisler in exchange for $1,500.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He led the NA in triples in 1875 with 13.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The National Association folded following the 1875 season, and Craver joined the 1876 New York Mutuals, a team that he also managed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] It was his only season in New York, as the Mutuals were expelled from the league for not making the required western trip.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] It was during this season that Craver was reputedly savagely beaten by a gambler for doublecrossing him on a fix.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He gained infamy the following season, his final season, when playing for the Louisville Grays.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] In 1877, the Grays were ahead in the league standings, with a 27–13 record with only 15 games left to play, but then lost their lead through horrible play, losing eight straight games at one point.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The trouble reportedly began when third baseman Bill Hague was injured and needed to be replaced.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] George Hall suggested that the team pick up his former Mutuals teammate Al Nichols.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The errors by Nichols, Hall, and Craver began to accumulate, and owner Charles Chase became suspicious when he noticed that Nichols was still in the lineup, even though Hague was fully healthy.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The players were soon seen around town with new clothes and jewelry.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Chase confronted pitcher Jim Devlin and did not receive a confession, but Hall thought Devlin had confessed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Hall claimed that Nichols was the person in contact with the gamblers and all three had thrown games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Chase requested from each member of the team permission to see all the Western Union telegrams sent and received.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Craver was the only man on the team to refuse, which caused him to be suspended.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] The telegrams proved the three were in open communication with the gamblers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] After his forced retirement from baseball, Craver became a police officer, along with fellow "criminal" Devlin.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] He began to receive military disability on July 1, 1892, as a result of time as a soldier, which would continue on to his widow, Catherine C.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/bill-craver] Craver died at the age of 57 of heart disease in his hometown of Troy, and is interred at Oakwood Cemetery.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] There is strong evidence both for and against Rothstein's involvement; however, there is no conclusive indication that the syndicate's actions were directed by or involved organized crime.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In response to the scandal, the National Baseball Commission was dissolved and Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis was appointed to be the first commissioner of baseball, given absolute control over the sport to restore its integrity.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite acquittals in a public trial in 1921, Landis permanently banned all eight implicated players from professional baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Baseball Hall of Fame eventually defined the punishment as banishment from consideration for the Hall.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite requests for reinstatement in the decades that followed (particularly in the case of Shoeless Joe Jackson), the ban remained in force for more than a century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In 2025, Commissioner Rob Manfred reinstated the Black Sox and several other now-deceased players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In 1919, Charles Comiskey, the owner of the Chicago White Sox and a prominent Major League Baseball (MLB) player from 1882 to 1894, was widely resented by his players for his miserliness.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey long had a reputation for underpaying players, even though the White Sox were one of the top teams in the league and had already won the 1917 World Series.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] This was a marked turnabout from Comiskey's days as a player, when he took part in the Players' League labor rebellion in 1890.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey was probably no worse than most owners of the time; in fact, the White Sox had the largest team payroll in 1919.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the era of the reserve clause, gamblers could find players on many teams looking for extra cash—and did.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The White Sox clubhouse was divided into two factions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] One group resented the more straitlaced players (later called the "Clean Sox"), a group that included second baseman Eddie Collins, catcher Ray Schalk, and pitchers Red Faber and Dickie Kerr.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] By contemporary accounts, the two factions rarely spoke to each other on or off the field, and the only thing they had in common was a resentment of Comiskey.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On September 18, 1919, White Sox player Chick Gandil met with Joe "Sport" Sullivan, a Boston bookmaker, at the Hotel Buckminster near Fenway Park.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The two men discussed plans to throw their upcoming series with the Cincinnati Reds for $80,000 ($1,575,000 in September 2025).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Two days later, a meeting of White Sox players—including those committed to going ahead with the fix and those just ready to listen to the proposal—took place in Gandil's room at the Ansonia Hotel in New York City.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Buck Weaver, the team's third baseman, was the only player to attend the meetings who did not receive money; nevertheless, he was later banned along with the other seven Black Sox for knowing about the fix but not reporting it.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Although he hardly played in the series, utility infielder Fred McMullin heard about the fix and threatened to report the others unless he was in on the payoff.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] As a small coincidence, McMullin was a former teammate of retired player William "Sleepy Bill" Burns, who had a minor role in the fix.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Both had played for the Los Angeles Angels of the Pacific Coast League (PCL), and Burns had previously pitched for the White Sox in 1909 and 1910.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Star outfielder "Shoeless Joe" Jackson was mentioned as a participant but did not attend the meetings, and his involvement remains disputed.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The scheme got an unexpected boost when the straitlaced Faber could not pitch due to getting sick with the flu.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Years later, Schalk said the fix would not have happened if Faber had been available.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] According to Schalk, since Faber was the ace of the staff, he would almost certainly have gotten starts that went instead to two of the alleged conspirators, pitchers Eddie "Knuckles" Cicotte and Lefty Williams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On October 1, the day of Game One, there were rumors amongst gamblers that the World Series was fixed, and a sudden influx of money being bet on Cincinnati caused the odds against them to fall rapidly.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] These rumors also reached the press box where several correspondents, including Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner* and ex-player and manager Christy Mathewson, resolved to compare notes on any plays and players that they felt were questionable.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, most fans and observers were taking the series at face value.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After throwing a strike with his first pitch of the Series, Cicotte's second pitch struck Cincinnati leadoff hitter Morrie Rath in the back, delivering a pre-arranged signal confirming the players' willingness to go through with the fix.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the fourth inning, Cicotte made a bad throw to Swede Risberg at second base.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Sportswriters found the unsuccessful double play to be suspicious.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams lost three games, a Series record.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Kerr, a rookie who was not part of the fix, won both of his starts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, the gamblers were now reneging on their promised progress payments (to be paid after each game lost), claiming that all the money was let out on bets and was in the hands of the bookmakers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After Game Five, angry about the non-payment of promised money, the players involved in the fix attempted to doublecross the gamblers and won Games Six and Seven of the best-of-nine Series.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Before Game Eight, threats of violence were made on the gamblers' behalf against players and family members.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams started Game Eight but gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before manager Kid Gleason relieved him.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The White Sox lost Game Eight (and the series) on October 9, 1919.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Besides Weaver, the players involved in the scandal received $5,000 each (equivalent to $93,000 in 2025) or more, with Gandil taking $35,000 (equivalent to $650,000 in 2025).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Rumors of the fix dogged the White Sox throughout the 1920 season as they battled the Cleveland Indians for the American League pennant, and stories of corruption touched players on other clubs as well.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] At last, in September 1920, a grand jury was convened to investigate; Cicotte confessed to his participation in the fix to the grand jury on September 28.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On the eve of their final season series, the White Sox were in a virtual tie for first place with the Indians.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Sox would need to win all three of their remaining games and then hope for Cleveland to stumble, as the Indians had more games left to play than the Sox.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite the season being on the line, Comiskey suspended the seven White Sox still in the majors (Gandil had not returned to the team in 1920 and was playing semi-pro ball).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He later said he had no choice but to suspend them, even though this action likely cost the Sox any chance of winning a second pennant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Sox lost two of the three games in the final series against the St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Louis Browns and finished in second place, two games behind the Indians, who went on to win the 1920 World Series.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The grand jury issued its decision on October 22, 1920, and eight players and five gamblers were implicated.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The indictments included nine counts of conspiracy to defraud.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The ten players not implicated in the scandal, as well as manager Kid Gleason, were each given $1,500 bonus checks (equivalent to $24,100 in 2025) by Comiskey in October 1920, the amount equaling the difference between the winners' and losers' share for participation in the 1919 Series.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The trial commenced in Chicago on June 27, 1921, but was delayed by Judge Hugo Friend because two defendants, Ben Franklin and Carl Zork, claimed to be ill.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Right fielder Shano Collins was named as the wronged party in the indictments, accusing his corrupt teammates of having cost him $1,784 as a result of the scandal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Before the trial, key evidence went missing from the Cook County courthouse, including the signed confessions of Cicotte and Jackson, who subsequently recanted their confessions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Some years later, the missing confessions reappeared in the possession of Comiskey's lawyer.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On July 1, the prosecution announced that Burns, who was under indictment for his part in the scandal, had turned state's evidence and would testify.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] During jury selection on July 11, several members of the current White Sox team, including Gleason, visited the courthouse, chatting and shaking hands with the indicted ex-players; at one point they even tickled Weaver, who was known to be quite ticklish.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Jury selection took several days, but on July 15 twelve jurors were finally empaneled in the case.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Trial testimony began on July 18, when prosecutor Charles Gorman outlined the evidence he planned to present against the defendants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey was then called to the stand, and became so agitated with questions being posed by the defense that he rose from the witness chair and shook his fist at the defendants' counsel, Ben Short.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After additional testimony and evidence, on July 28 the defense rested and the case went to the jury.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The jury deliberated for less than three hours before returning verdicts of not guilty on all charges for all of the accused players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Long before the scandal broke, many of baseball's owners had nursed longstanding grievances with the way the game was then governed by the National Baseball Commission.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Black Sox scandal and the damage it caused to the game's reputation gave owners the resolve to make significant changes to the governance of the sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Their original plan was to appoint the widely respected federal judge and noted baseball fan Kenesaw Mountain Landis to head a reformed three-member commission comprising men unconnected to baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, Landis made it clear to the owners that he would accept only an appointment as the game's sole commissioner, and even then only on the condition that he be granted essentially unchecked power over the sport.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Desperate to clean up the game's image, the owners agreed to his terms and vested him with virtually unlimited authority over everyone in the major and minor leagues.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] It was controversial at the time for MLB to move toward a single commissioner with sole governance on behalf of the owners.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Following their acquittals, Landis quickly quashed any prospect that he might reinstate the accused players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Making use of a precedent that had previously seen Babe Borton, Harl Maggert, Gene Dale and Bill Rumler banned from the PCL for fixing games, Landis made it clear that all eight accused players would remain on the "ineligible list," banning them from organized baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Landis took the position that while the players had been acquitted in court, there was no dispute they had broken the rules of baseball, and none of them could ever be allowed back in the game if it were to regain the public's trust.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey supported Landis by giving the seven who remained under contract to the White Sox their unconditional release.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Following the commissioner's statement, it was universally understood that all eight implicated players were to be banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He established the precedent that the league vested the commissioner with plenary power and the responsibility to determine the fitness or suitability of anyone, anything, or any circumstance, to be associated with professional baseball, past, present and future.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Also banned was Joe Gedeon, second baseman for the St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] A friend of Risberg, Gedeon learned about the fix from Risberg and placed bets on Cincinnati.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He informed Comiskey of the fix after the Series to gain a reward.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Instead, Landis banned him for life along with the eight White Sox.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The extent of Jackson's part in the scheme remains controversial.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He had a Series-leading .375 batting average—including the Series' only home run—threw out five baserunners and handled thirty chances in the outfield with no errors.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In general, players perform worse in games their team loses, and Jackson batted worse in the five games that the White Sox lost, with a batting average of .286 in losing games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] This was still an above-average batting average (the National and American Leagues hit a combined .263 in the 1919 season).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Jackson hit .351 for the season, fourth-best in the major leagues (his .356 career batting average is the fourth-best in history, surpassed only by Ty Cobb, Oscar Charleston and Rogers Hornsby) – each an MLB batting average leader.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Three of his six RBIs came in the losses, including the aforementioned home run, and a double in Game Eight when the Reds had a significant lead and the series was all but over.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Still, in that game, a long foul ball was caught at the fence with runners on second and third, depriving Jackson of a chance to drive in the runners.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] One play in particular has been subjected to scrutiny.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the fifth inning of Game Four, with a Cincinnati player on second, Jackson fielded a single hit to left field and threw home, which was cut off by Cicotte.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Gandil later admitted to yelling at Cicotte to intercept the throw.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Cicotte, whose guilt is undisputed, made two errors in that fifth inning alone.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Years later, all the implicated players said that Jackson was never present at their meetings with the gamblers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams, Jackson's roommate, later said they mentioned Jackson only in hopes of giving them more credibility with the gamblers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After being banned, Risberg and several other members of the Black Sox tried to organize a three-state barnstorming tour.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, they were forced to cancel those plans after Landis let it be known that anyone who played with or against them would also be banned from baseball for life.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] They then announced plans to play a regular exhibition game every Sunday in Chicago, but the Chicago City Council threatened to cancel the license of any ballpark that hosted them.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] With seven of their best players permanently sidelined, the White Sox crashed into seventh place in 1921 and would not be a contender in a pennant race again until 1936, five years after Comiskey's death.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] They would not win another American League championship until 1959 (a then-record forty-year gap) nor another World Series until 2005, prompting some to comment about a Curse of the Black Sox.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Although many believe the Black Sox name to be related to the dark and corrupt nature of the conspiracy, the term "Black Sox" may already have existed before the fix.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] There is a story that the name "Black Sox" derived from Comiskey's refusal to pay for the players' uniforms to be laundered, instead insisting that the players themselves pay for the cleaning.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] As the story goes, the players refused, and subsequent games saw the White Sox play in progressively filthier uniforms as dirt, sweat and grime collected on the white, woolen uniforms until they took on a much darker shade.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey then had the uniforms washed and deducted the laundry bill from the players' salaries.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On the other hand, Eliot Asinof in his book *Eight Men Out* makes no such connection, mentioning the filthy uniforms early on but referring to the term "Black Sox" only in connection with the scandal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The **Boston Braves** were a Major League Baseball team that played in Boston for the National League from 1871 to 1952.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The team relocated to Milwaukee after the 1952 season, becoming the Milwaukee Braves, and subsequently moved to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] During its 82-year stay in Massachusetts, the franchise was known by various nicknames, including the **Red Stockings**, **Red Caps**, **Beaneaters**, **Rustlers**, **Bees**, and "Braves".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Their longest-lasting nickname was inspired by Tamanend, a chief of the Lenni-Lenape in the Delaware Valley.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] While in Boston, the team won 10 National League pennants and a World Series championship in 1914 that came after a season in which the Braves were in last place as late as July 15—a turnaround that led to the nickname "Miracle Braves".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1948, the Braves reached the World Series largely as a result of their two dominant pitchers, Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who inspired the *Boston Post* slogan "Spahn and Sain and pray for rain." The Braves posted a losing record in all but 12 of the 38 seasons after their World Series win.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Boston franchise played at South End Grounds from 1871 to 1914 and at Braves Field from 1915 to 1952.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Braves Field is now Nickerson Field of Boston University.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The franchise, from Boston to Milwaukee to Atlanta, is the oldest continuously operating professional baseball franchise.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Boston Braves had an overall win–loss record of 5,118–5,598–138 (.478) during their 77-year major-league tenure in Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Six former Boston Braves players have been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Cincinnati Red Stockings, established in 1869 as the first openly all-professional baseball team, voted to dissolve after the 1870 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Player-manager Harry Wright then went to Boston, Massachusetts—at the invitation of Boston businessman Ivers Whitney Adams—with brother George Wright and two other Cincinnati players joined the **Boston Red Stockings**, a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] This team and its successors are the oldest continuously playing team in American professional sports.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Led by the Wright brothers, Barnes, and Spalding, the Red Stockings won four of the National Association's five championships.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The team became one of the National League's charter franchises in 1876, sometimes called the "**Red Caps**" (as a new Cincinnati Red Stockings club was another charter member).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Boston came to be called the **Beaneaters** by sportswriters in 1883, while retaining red as the team color.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Red Caps/Beaneaters won eight pennants during the 19th century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Their manager was Frank Selee, the first manager not to double as a player as well.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The 1898 team finished 102–47, a club record for wins that would stand for almost a century.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1894 the Braves became the first major league baseball team to wear letterforms on their uniform caps when they added a monogram-style device to their front.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1897, the Beaneaters, as runner-up in the National League, took part in the 1897 Temple Cup championship series against the Baltimore Orioles, losing in five games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] They only managed one winning season from 1900 to 1913, and lost 100 or more games six times.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1907, the renamed Doves (temporarily) eliminated the red from their stockings because their manager thought the red dye could cause wounds to become infected (as noted in *The Sporting News Baseball Guide* during the 1940s when each team's entry had a history of its nickname(s).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] See details in History of baseball team nicknames).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The American League club's owner, Charles Taylor, changed his team's name to the Red Sox in place of the "Americans".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] When George and John Dovey acquired the club in 1907, the team was named the **Doves**; when purchased by William Hepburn Russell in 1911 reporters tried out **Rustlers.** The team adopted an official name, the **Braves**, for the first time in 1912.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Their owner, James Gaffney, a member of New York City's Tammany Hall, tributed the team to Tamanend, "The Patron Saint of America," with the name and his image as the logo.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Two years later, the Braves put together one of the most memorable seasons in baseball history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After a dismal 4–18 start, the Braves seemed to be on pace for a last place finish.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] On July 4, 1914, the Braves lost both games of a doubleheader to the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The consecutive losses put their record at 26–40 and the Braves were in last place, 15 games behind the league-leading New York Giants, who had won the previous three league pennants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After a day off, the Braves put together a hot streak, and from July 6 through September 5, the Braves won 41 games against only 12 losses.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] On September 7 and 8, the Braves took 2 of 3 from the New York Giants and moved into first place.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves tore through September and early October, closing with 25 wins against 6 losses, while the Giants went 16–16.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] They are the only team to win a pennant after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] They were in last place as late as July 18, but were close to the pack, moving into fourth on July 21 and second place on August 12.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Despite their comeback, the Braves entered the World Series as a heavy underdog to Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Nevertheless, the Braves swept the Athletics—the first unqualified sweep in the young history of the modern World Series (the 1907 World Series had one tied game)—to win the world championship.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Meanwhile, former Chicago Cubs infielder Johnny Evers, in his second season with the Braves, won the Chalmers Award.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves played the World Series (as well as the last few weeks of the 1914 regular season) at Fenway Park, since their normal home, the South End Grounds, was too small.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] However, the Braves' success inspired owner Gaffney to build a modern park, Braves Field, which opened in August 1915.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] It was the largest park in the majors at the time, with 40,000 seats and also a very spacious outfield.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The park was novel for its time; public transportation brought fans right into the park.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After contending for most of 1915 and 1916, the Braves spent much of the next 19 years in mediocrity, during which they posted only three winning seasons (1921, 1933, and 1934).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The lone highlight of those years came when Giants' attorney Emil Fuchs bought the team in 1923 to bring his longtime friend, pitching great Christy Mathewson, back into the game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Although original plans called for Mathewson to be the principal owner, he had never recovered from tuberculosis that he had contracted after being gassed during World War I.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] By the end of the 1923 season, it was obvious Mathewson could not continue even in a reduced role, and he would die two years later, with the result that Fuchs was permanently given the presidency.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1928, the Braves traded for Hall of Famer Rogers Hornsby who had a very productive year in his only season with Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He batted .387 to win his seventh and final batting championship.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Fuchs was committed to building a winner, but the damage from the years before his arrival took some time to overcome.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves finally managed to compete in 1933 and 1934 under manager Bill McKechnie, but Fuchs' revenue was severely depleted due to the Great Depression.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Looking for a way to get more supporters and more money, Fuchs worked out a deal with the New York Yankees to acquire Babe Ruth, who had, coincidentally, started his career with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Fuchs named Ruth vice president and assistant manager of the Braves, and promised him a share of team profits.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He was also to be consulted on all player transactions.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Fuchs even suggested that Ruth, who had long had his heart set on managing, could take over as manager once McKechnie stepped down—perhaps as early as 1936.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] At first, it looked like Ruth was the final piece the team needed in 1935.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] On opening day, he had a hand in all of the Braves' runs in a 4–2 win over the Giants.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Opening Day proved to be the only time the Braves were over .500 all year.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] A 4–20 May ended any realistic chance of contention.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] At the same time, it became apparent that Ruth was finished even as a part-time player.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] While his high living of previous years had begun catching up with him a year earlier, his conditioning rapidly declined in the first month of 1935.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] While he was still able to hit at first, he could do little else.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He could no longer run, and his fielding was so terrible that three of the Braves' pitchers threatened to go on strike if Ruth were in the lineup.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Ruth soon discovered that he was vice president and assistant manager in name only, and Fuchs' promise of a share of team profits was hot air.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In fact, Ruth discovered that Fuchs expected him to invest some of *his* money in the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Seeing a franchise in complete disarray, Ruth retired on June 1, only six days after he clouted what turned out to be the last three home runs of his career, in what remains one of the most memorable afternoons in baseball history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He had wanted to quit as early as May 12, but Fuchs wanted him to hang on so he could play in every National League park.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] By this time, the Braves were 9–27, their season all but over.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] They ultimately finished 38–115, easily the worst season in franchise history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Their .248 winning percentage is tied for the seventh-worst in baseball history, and the sixth-worst in National League history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] It is the second-worst in modern baseball history (behind only the 1916 Philadelphia Athletics), and the worst in modern National League history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Insolvent like his team, Fuchs was forced to give up control of the Braves in August 1935.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The principal financial backer for the team, Charles F.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Adams, was banned by Commissioner Landis from taking control of the team because Adams owned Suffolk Downs race track.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Quinn did not care for the Braves name, possibly because it was linked to former owner Gaffney and to New York's Tammany Hall politics and launched a contest for the general public with the regional sportswriters being the judges.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Among 13,000 votes of 1,327 potential names, the team was renamed to the **Boston Bees** Keeping up with the Bees theme, Braves Field became nicknamed the Bee Hive.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] This did little to change the team's fortunes.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After five uneven years, a new owner, construction magnate Lou Perini, changed the nickname back to the Braves.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1948, the team won the National League pennant by capturing 91 games to finish 61⁄2 places ahead of the second–place St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] They also attracted 1,455,439 fans to Braves Field, the third-largest gate in the National League and a high-water mark for the team's stay in Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The pitching staff was anchored by Hall of Famer Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who won 39 games between them.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The poem received such a wide audience that the sentiment, usually now paraphrased as "Spahn, Sain, then pray for rain" or "Spahn, Sain and two days of rain", entered the baseball vocabulary.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Ironically, in the 1948 season, the Braves actually had a better record in games that Spahn and Sain *did not* start than in games they did.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves lost the 1948 World Series in six games to the Cleveland Indians (who had beaten the Red Sox in a tie-breaker game to spoil an all-Boston World Series).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] This turned out to be the Braves' last hurrah in Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Acquired earlier by trade from the Brooklyn Dodgers, on April 18, 1950, Sam "Jet" Jethroe was added to the Boston Braves roster.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Dodgers had another young CF in Duke Snider rising in their system, resulting in the trade to the Braves.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Going on to be named National League Rookie of the Year at age 32, Jethroe broke the color barrier with Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] In 1950, Jethroe hit .273 with 100 runs, 18 home runs and 58 RBI.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] His 35 stolen bases led the National League, a feat he would duplicate in 1951.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] While in Boston, Jethroe was a roommate of Chuck Cooper, of the Boston Celtics who was the first African-American player drafted by an NBA team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] A former Negro leagues star and military veteran, Jethroe remains the oldest player to have won Rookie of the Year honors.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Amid four mediocre seasons after 1948, attendance steadily dwindled, even though Braves Field had the reputation of being more family friendly than Fenway.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] For a half century, the major leagues had not had a single franchise move.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves played their last home game in Boston on September 21, 1952, losing to the Brooklyn Dodgers 8–2 before 8,822 at Braves Field; the home attendance for the 1952 season was under 282,000.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] On March 13, 1953, owner Lou Perini said that he would seek permission from the National League to move the Braves to Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After the franchise's long history in Boston, the day became known as "Black Friday" in the city as fans mourned the team's exit after eight decades.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Perini, however, pointed to dwindling attendance as the main reason for the move.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He also announced that he had recently bought out his original partners.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] He announced Milwaukee as that was where the Braves had their top farm club, the Brewers.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Milwaukee had long been a possible target for moving.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Louis Browns there earlier the same year (Milwaukee was the original home of that franchise), but his proposal had been voted down by the other American League owners.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Going into spring training in 1953, it appeared that the Braves would play another year in Boston unless the National League gave permission for the move.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After a 31⁄2-hour meeting at the Vinoy Park Hotel in St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] Petersburg, Florida, league approval was granted after Perini promised not to sell the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] During a game against the New York Yankees on March 18, the sale was announced final and that the team would move to Milwaukee, immediately.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The All-Star Game had been scheduled for Braves Field.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] It was moved to Crosley Field and hosted by the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves franchise moved their triple-A Brewers from Milwaukee to Toledo, Ohio.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] After the Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1953, the Braves Field site was sold to Boston University and reconstructed as Nickerson Field, the home of many Boston University teams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-scandal/boston-red-caps] The Braves Field scoreboard was sold to the Kansas City A's and used at Municipal Stadium; the A's moved to Oakland after the 1967 season.
